Shares of the following companies
may have  unusual (JCI)  moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and share prices are as of the previous close.  The Jakarta Composite index rose less than 0.1 percent to
3,797.15. The market was closed yesterday for a public holiday.  Coal producers: Power-station coal  prices  at Australia’s
Newcastle port, an Asian benchmark, rose 2.3 percent to $112.85
a metric ton in the week ended Dec. 23.  PT Bumi Resources (BUMI)  , Asia’s biggest exporter of the fuel, dropped 1.2 percent to
2,150 rupiah and  PT Adaro Energy (ADRO)  , Indonesia’s second-
largest coal producer, slipped 0.6 percent to 1,770 rupiah.  Energy companies: Crude oil futures gained for a sixth day,
advancing as much as 0.5 percent to $100.13 a barrel in after-
hours trading in New York.  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC)  , Indonesia’s biggest listed oil company, was unchanged at
2,475 rupiah and  PT Energi Mega Persada (ENRG)  , the second
largest, declined 2.3 percent to 173 rupiah.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
